  "prompt": "What is the difference between angular velocity and angular acceleration?",
  "response": "The difference between angular velocity and angular acceleration lies in what they describe and how they relate to angular motion:\n\n**Angular Velocity (\u03c9 - Omega):**\n\n*   **What it describes:** The rate at which an object is rotating or revolving around an axis. In simpler terms, how fast something is spinning or going in a circle.\n*   **Units:** Radians per second (rad/s), degrees per second (\u00b0/s), revolutions per minute (RPM), etc.\n*   **Analogy to Linear Motion:** It's the rotational equivalent of linear velocity (speed in a particular direction).\n*   **Equation:**  \u03c9 = \u0394\u03b8 / \u0394t (change in angular position / change in time)\n*   **Key Aspects:**\n    *   **Magnitude:**  How fast the rotation is.\n    *   **Direction:** Represented by a vector along the axis of rotation.  The direction is determined by the right-hand rule (curl fingers of your right hand in the direction of rotation, and your thumb points in the direction of the angular velocity vector).\n*   **Constant Angular Velocity:**  The object is rotating at a steady rate, neither speeding up nor slowing down.\n\n**Angular Acceleration (\u03b1 - Alpha):**\n\n*   **What it describes:** The rate at which the angular velocity is changing. In simpler terms, how quickly the spinning or circular motion is speeding up or slowing down.\n*   **Units:** Radians per second squared (rad/s\u00b2), degrees per second squared (\u00b0/s\u00b2), etc.\n*   **Analogy to Linear Motion:** It's the rotational equivalent of linear acceleration (change in velocity over time).\n*   **Equation:** \u03b1 = \u0394\u03c9 / \u0394t (change in angular velocity / change in time)\n*   **Key Aspects:**\n    *   **Magnitude:**  How quickly the angular velocity is changing.\n    *   **Direction:** Represented by a vector along the axis of rotation.\n        *   If \u03b1 and \u03c9 point in the same direction, the object is speeding up.\n        *   If \u03b1 and \u03c9 point in opposite directions, the object is slowing down.\n*   **Constant Angular Acceleration:**  The angular velocity is changing at a steady rate.\n\n**Here's a table summarizing the key differences:**\n\n| Feature           | Angular Velocity (\u03c9)              | Angular Acceleration (\u03b1)                |\n|--------------------|------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------|\n| **Describes**     | Rate of rotation/revolution       | Rate of change of angular velocity      |\n| **Analogy**        | Linear Velocity                    | Linear Acceleration                     |\n| **Units**          | rad/s, RPM, \u00b0/s                    | rad/s\u00b2, \u00b0/s\u00b2                           |\n| **Equation**        | \u03c9 = \u0394\u03b8 / \u0394t                        | \u03b1 = \u0394\u03c9 / \u0394t                             |\n| **Tells you...**  | How fast something is spinning    | How quickly the spinning is changing    |\n| **Vector Direction**| Along axis of rotation (RHR)       | Along axis of rotation (RHR), indicates speeding up or slowing down based on relationship to the angular velocity vector|\n\n**Example:**\n\nImagine a spinning figure skater:\n\n*   **Angular Velocity:**  Describes how many revolutions per second they are making.  A high angular velocity means they are spinning very fast.\n*   **Angular Acceleration:**  Describes how quickly they are increasing or decreasing their spinning rate. If they pull their arms in, they experience a positive angular acceleration (they spin faster). If they extend their arms, they experience a negative angular acceleration (they slow down).\n",
